english:
  title: A Casual Composition at Paekhcheon County
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Following where my horse wanders, I sing at the northern edge of the sea.
    Heaven sends forth magnificent vistas to my passing carriage.
    Cool cicadas, hidden in leaves, cry out in the parasol trees of the county.
    Rain-soaked swallows, clinging to branches, gather in the willow villages.

    The ruddy sunset scatters away, and flowers have borne their fruit.
    Breaking through the surging waves, barley shoots forth again in tender growth.
    Turning my head to gaze where the wild geese fly,
    The grass-green reaching to the sky troubles this wanderer's heart.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem uses the changing seasons and natural phenomena as metaphors for transience and cyclical renewal—a common theme in East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The final image of geese flying and grass touching sky evokes the melancholy of the traveler contemplating distance and impermanence.
